European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the occupation by the Nazis.
Maybe it is because of living in a country in the middle of Europe, a place that for centuries has been a crossroads of ideological currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations in Europe.
Perhaps all these factors, combined, have led me to conclude that Europe represents a single political entity whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could always be two Europes – one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and another less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated – is a mistake.
This is like heating up one part of a room while keeping another part cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event echoes across Europe.
If Europe is to become united, if the European Union is to integrate the new post-communist democracies – which is in Europe's interest – a series of essential tasks must be addressed within these new democracies as well as within the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must promote community spirit in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a vibrant society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies become an organic part of a shared continental commitment to deepening and strengthening civil society.
The more diverse European civil societal structures become and the more interconnected they are, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer various solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and nonprofit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economically efficient it will be; and the better it will address those social needs that central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity becomes more authentic when it is closely linked to people or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy with its abandonment of European solidarity, which led to the capitulation at Munich.
This experience remains a strong call for vigilance.
Evil must be confronted as soon as it appears, but it is not enough if governments act alone.
For government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern about security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is working intensively on a new concept of its security policy.
It should stand out for its ability to make quick decisions and to implement joint decisions swiftly – reforms that have been shown to be necessary by recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year showed that respect for human life and human freedom, as well as the interests of pan-European security, require interventions beyond the EU borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action is, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where the UN mandate might not be available, even though an intervention is in the interest of many people, indeed of all of Europe, and even of human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to enhance Europe's material and technical preparedness.
But more is needed in terms of preventive security, and it is also necessary for this security to reflect the values of Europe's extended civil society.
Tens of thousands of lives and enormous amounts of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the onset of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, action was taken only timidly.
These failures resulted from a variety of individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be witnessing the horrors in Kosovo.
Europe cannot remain permanently dependent on the USA, especially when it comes to European problems.
It must be able to agree on solutions on its own.
It is unimaginable that the EU can remain a respected part of the world order if it proves incapable of agreeing on means and ways to protect human rights not only on its territory but also in areas that may one day join it.
Such EU expansion is only feasible if it goes hand in hand with a determined reform of EU institutions.
I hope confidently that the intergovernmental conference on institutional reform will present practical proposals for advancing the union.
But I see this as the beginning of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a lasting effort to speed up and make more transparent EU decision-making.
A point related to institutional reform is how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not be simply overwhelmed by the larger ones, while still taking each state's size into proper consideration.
A possibility could be the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber would be elected from their own ranks by the parliaments of the member states, not directly.
The first chamber of the EU – i.e., the current Parliament – would thus reflect the size of individual member states, whereas the second chamber, with an equal number of representatives for each state, would enhance equality.
At some point, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution – a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution requires two parts.
Part one would define the rights and duties of both European citizens and states, the underlying values, and the significance and goals of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their fundamental powers, and their relationships to each other.
Such a constitution would not mean an automatic transformation of the current Union into the federal superstate feared by Euroskeptics.
However, it would help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, understand it better, see its relevance to their lives, and thus identify with it.
